			<td class="BoardRowB" colspan=3>
				I do agree with you that the writer is not guilty by mere fact of writing a story. Just like Stephen King, Koontz, Anne Rice, Poe, Thomas Harris, etc. <br>  <br> I think what shocks me more than an Anne Rice story is that Anne Rice writes about Lestat or Louise, or some other fictional character from her head that she dreamed up. Totally unique people that she put in the book and acted out on pages to unfold a drama, or to depict horrific imagery. <br>  <br> This guy wrote a story based on character's he enjoys acting out/playing. These are characters in the game that he actively roleplays. It's not from a 3rd person point of view, it's not descriptive of things that might happen from an evil character (Silence of the Lambs), this is a guy who's writing stories based on the characters he's fantasizing about/playing out in a game. <br>  <br> That's the largest part that gets me. Like someone mentioned before, watch 8mm, and how they played out &quot;snuff films&quot;. The fascination and the representation of sexual brutality in a first-person sense is a tad bit sick. <br>  <br> I actually like watching &quot;Beyond the Grave&quot; or shows, and reading books about forensic research on murders, overviews of killers and what they do. But this guy likes to write/act it out with his &quot;fantasy characters&quot;. See my point of view? <br>  <br>  <br> Cymric <br> Innoruuk.Com<p>

							

